WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:18.360
All right, we've just talked about firewall technologies and just to refocus here, firewall

00:18.360 --> 00:37.600
technologies are, all right, we've just talked about firewall technologies and just to refocus

00:37.600 --> 00:43.720
here, firewall technologies are what allows us to be able to make decisions. So we talked

00:43.720 --> 00:49.720
about simple packet filtering, we talked about state full firewalls, we talked about proxy

00:49.720 --> 00:55.480
firewalls. In this module, we're going to discuss what are called firewall architectures.

00:55.480 --> 01:01.480
Now, what's the difference? Well, firewall architectures are how we can architect those

01:01.480 --> 01:07.240
technologies that we just discussed in the best way possible. And so we're going to show

01:07.240 --> 01:12.520
you from a diagram perspective what these architectures actually look like. And you're

01:12.520 --> 01:17.240
going to see that we're going to progress from the simplest architecture to some of the ones

01:17.240 --> 01:22.760
that companies obviously use today to provide the best level of security. So these are called

01:22.760 --> 01:28.680
firewall architectures. And it's important for you on the exam to focus on those keywords

01:28.680 --> 01:35.000
and decide whether and look at whether the question is talking about firewall technologies

01:35.000 --> 01:41.640
or firewall architectures. These are architectures. Let's start with the simplest one. In fact,

01:41.640 --> 01:48.440
this is a summary of what we're going to look at. These are standard names that the industry

01:48.440 --> 01:55.480
uses for firewall architectures. Starting with simple packet filtering and then improving to what

01:55.480 --> 02:02.920
we call dual home host firewall architecture, a screened host firewall architecture and screen

02:02.920 --> 02:11.000
subnet firewall architectures. And they're listed by increasing security if you want to look at it

02:11.000 --> 02:17.800
that way. So let's start with the simplest one, which is a packet filtering firewall. And basically

02:17.800 --> 02:24.440
looks exactly like this. We've got our internal network here. We're connected to the internet or

02:24.440 --> 02:32.120
some other network that we don't trust. And so what we place in between is a simple router. And

02:32.120 --> 02:39.720
because a router operates at layer three, the only decisions that it can make is what's available

02:39.720 --> 02:46.200
at layer three. In other words, the header portion of the datagram is what the router can make

02:46.200 --> 02:54.520
decisions on. So very simple decisions like source port or source IP address, destination IP

02:54.520 --> 03:00.760
address, the type of packet that it is, the service that's being requested. Those are the simple

03:00.760 --> 03:07.320
type of decisions that a router can make based on the intelligence that it has. What would be good

03:07.320 --> 03:14.120
about this is that it would be very efficient but very limited in the type of decisions that it

03:14.120 --> 03:21.560
can make. Now let's get better. And if you look at this diagram, what would be better is if we

03:21.560 --> 03:30.200
replace the router with something else that understands the entire OSI model layers. In fact, we would

03:30.280 --> 03:38.360
call that a host or a computer. So instead of a router in between our internal network and the

03:38.360 --> 03:45.480
internet, we place a computer or a host. And because it's a computer, it can understand all seven

03:45.480 --> 03:52.040
layers of the OSI model. And so if you remember back to those firewall technologies that we just

03:52.040 --> 03:59.320
looked at in the previous module, this would be able to run them all or a combination of them all.

03:59.320 --> 04:05.320
It could do simple packet filtering at the network layer. It could do stateful inspection

04:05.320 --> 04:11.480
also at the network layer. But this because it's a computer could also be running proxy firewalls

04:11.480 --> 04:18.600
like circuit level or application level. So it's a better architecture simply because it's able to

04:18.600 --> 04:24.520
run any of those firewall technologies that we talked about before because it really is a

04:24.520 --> 04:31.400
computer that understands all seven layers. Now let's get even better than this. If you were to

04:31.400 --> 04:37.720
suggest what something might be even better than this, why don't we combine the two that we just

04:37.720 --> 04:45.880
saw. So let's put a router on the outside here facing the internet and let's keep the host

04:45.880 --> 04:53.000
in the middle. And this would look like right here. The idea of this and it's called a screened

04:53.000 --> 05:00.920
host firewall architecture is the router can handle the first level of decision making that it

05:00.920 --> 05:07.880
is subjected to. And then anything that gets through the router can be handled by the host now

05:07.880 --> 05:14.760
that can be running proxy firewalls and anything else. Now this serves a second purpose as well

05:14.760 --> 05:22.280
because the router that's facing the outside can act as a screen or a protection mechanism for the

05:22.280 --> 05:28.440
host that's on the inside. Any attacker that wants to get to the host first of all has to be able to

05:28.440 --> 05:34.600
compromise and get through the router itself. So this can act as a screen and that's why it's actually

05:34.600 --> 05:43.080
called a screened host firewall architecture. Now we can even get better than this because what we

05:43.080 --> 05:49.640
can do is and we've talked many times in this course how good network security requires us to

05:49.640 --> 05:56.760
monitor incoming traffic into the internal network because we want to protect the value of what's

05:56.760 --> 06:03.880
in here. But companies today need to also monitor what's going out of the network. And in many cases

06:03.880 --> 06:10.360
that might be even more important. And the reason for that is for data loss prevention. But there

06:10.360 --> 06:16.440
could also be some machines on the inside of the network here that are being used as a channel to

06:16.440 --> 06:23.240
attack others for distributed denial service for example. So if we monitored outgoing traffic

06:23.240 --> 06:30.120
as well as incoming that's a better way to approach network security. So the next architecture

06:30.120 --> 06:37.560
really means let's put a router on the inside as well so that we can protect from the inside and

06:37.560 --> 06:43.880
monitor what's going out. So that architecture would look something like this and this is the

06:43.880 --> 06:50.440
architecture that gives companies the ability to start creating what are called subnetworks like

06:50.440 --> 06:57.480
your DMZ where you would put services in there that are required from the outside. And the bottom

06:57.480 --> 07:04.200
line here is that if you're allowing people out on the internet to interface with us to order

07:04.200 --> 07:11.320
our products and services and pay us for example you need applications to be able to do that.

07:11.320 --> 07:16.520
And it would not make sense to have those applications running on the inside of the network

07:16.520 --> 07:22.600
because then you'd be allowing people to get right into the internal network that are not trusted.

07:22.600 --> 07:29.640
And so what we do is we place those services, those web applications and servers that are required

07:29.640 --> 07:35.960
from the outside in your DMZ here so that we can ultimately protect our internal network and

07:35.960 --> 07:44.360
channel all of that traffic up into this subnetwork here where we can protect what's in there as well

07:44.360 --> 07:51.880
but we can monitor what's going on but ultimately we're not putting our internal network at risk.

07:51.880 --> 08:00.120
And so anything in here can be accessed from the outside and so this is what we call a screened

08:00.200 --> 08:07.000
subnet firewall architecture where everything is channeled into here but we can protect and monitor

08:07.000 --> 08:13.560
what's going in here so that ultimately no untrusted entities are actually allowed to come into

08:13.560 --> 08:19.960
our internal network and we can also monitor anything that is going out to the internet for data

08:19.960 --> 08:27.080
loss prevention and to prevent outgoing denial of service attacks. This is what we call the screen

08:27.080 --> 08:38.040
subnet firewall architecture. Now some people also refer to a number of legs that a firewall

08:38.040 --> 08:44.760
might have and in this case this would be referred to as a three-legged firewall because if you

08:44.760 --> 08:50.600
look at this firewall that's in the middle it's got three legs doesn't it one leg is connected to

08:50.680 --> 08:57.640
the internal network one leg is connected to the DMZ and the other leg is connected to the outside

08:57.640 --> 09:05.640
internet but there's nothing stopping companies from having four legs or five legs or a hundred

09:05.640 --> 09:12.600
legs or legs within other legs so the bottom line is companies can get pretty creative in how they

09:12.600 --> 09:19.320
structure how they they first of all put their firewalls in here and how they offer functionality

09:19.320 --> 09:25.160
related to services that may be required so you can get pretty creative not only in the functionality

09:25.160 --> 09:34.200
in how you set this up but also in the security so you could have n-legged firewalls depending on how

09:34.200 --> 09:40.040
your network has been set up and the services that you want to be able to offer to the outside

09:40.040 --> 09:42.040
internet ultimately

